        name: 'Jo (Josephine)',
        description:
          'Jo is the play\'s protagonist: a sharp, creative, emotionally guarded seventeen-year-old girl navigating poverty, an absent mother, pregnancy, and the search for identity and belonging. She is intelligent and perceptive, with a dry, often self-deprecating wit that she uses as a defence mechanism against the instability of her life. Her artistic talent — she draws constantly — suggests an inner life and sensitivity that she rarely allows others to see. Jo\'s central struggle is to define herself against her mother\'s example: she is terrified of repeating Helen\'s patterns of failed relationships and neglectful parenting, yet she finds herself in an increasingly similar situation as her pregnancy progresses. Her relationship with Jimmie is genuine but brief, offering warmth and physical affection that she has never received from Helen. Her relationship with Geof is more complex: she accepts his domestic care and emotional support but resists the deeper intimacy he offers, perhaps because she has learned to distrust dependence on others. Jo\'s occasional cruelty — her barbed comments to Geof about his sexuality, her dismissiveness towards Helen — reveals the damage that years of neglect have inflicted on her capacity for trust. Yet she is also capable of tenderness, humour, and surprising resilience. Delaney refuses to sentimentalise Jo or to present her as a passive victim; she is a fully realised, contradictory, deeply human character.',
        keyQuotes: [
          {
            quote: 'I\'m not sorry and I\'m not glad. I don\'t know what I am.',
            analysis:
              'Jo\'s response when discussing her pregnancy captures her characteristic emotional honesty and confusion. The tripartite structure — "not sorry," "not glad," "don\'t know" — moves from negation to uncertainty, reflecting Jo\'s refusal to perform the expected emotions. This line encapsulates her liminal position throughout the play: caught between childhood and adulthood, between her mother\'s world and a future she cannot yet imagine.'
          },
          {
            quote: 'I\'ll never look at anything. I hate it. I don\'t want to be a mother.',
            analysis:
              'Jo\'s panicked rejection of motherhood reveals her deepest fear: that she will become Helen. The emphatic negatives — "never," "hate," "don\'t want" — convey genuine terror rather than mere reluctance. Delaney uses this moment to show how the cycle of poor parenting perpetuates itself: Jo\'s anxiety is a direct consequence of her own experience of being mothered badly, and her fear threatens to undermine her ability to parent her own child.'
          },
          {
            quote: 'We don\'t ask for life, we have it thrust upon us.',
            analysis:
              'This philosophical reflection reveals Jo\'s intelligence and her sense that life is something that happens to her rather than something she controls. The passive construction — life is "thrust upon us" — echoes her situation throughout the play, where events (her mother\'s departure, her pregnancy) are imposed rather than chosen. Yet the statement also has a resigned courage: Jo acknowledges the harshness of existence without self-pity.'
          },
          {
            quote: 'I\'m an extraordinary person. There\'s only one of me like there\'s only one of you.',
            analysis:
              'Jo\'s assertion of uniqueness is both a defiant declaration of self-worth and a poignant reminder of her isolation. The word "extraordinary" insists on her specialness in a world that consistently treats her as ordinary or insignificant. The extension — "like there\'s only one of you" — generalises the claim, suggesting that every individual deserves recognition. Delaney gives Jo a philosophical voice that transcends her social circumstances, asserting the dignity of working-class experience without sentimentality.'
          },
          {
            quote: 'In this country there are only the knackered and the knackered and the bloody knackered.',
            analysis:
              'Jo\'s bleak assessment of social mobility in Britain uses the deliberately crude repetition of "knackered" — slang for exhausted or broken — to reject the fantasy of class hierarchy. By refusing to distinguish between social levels, Jo suggests that poverty is universal among the working class, with no meaningful gradation of suffering. The vulgarity of the language is itself a political statement: Delaney puts working-class speech on the stage without sanitising it, challenging middle-class theatrical decorum.'
          }
        ]
