        name: 'Geof (Geoffrey)',
        description:
          'Geof is a quiet, gentle, homosexual art student who moves in with Jo during her pregnancy and becomes her primary source of emotional and practical support. He is the play\'s most unambiguously sympathetic character: kind, patient, domestically competent, and genuinely devoted to Jo\'s wellbeing. Geof represents an alternative model of masculinity and domesticity — he cooks, cleans, prepares for the baby, and offers emotional care without demanding sexual or romantic reciprocation. His homosexuality, while never explicitly confirmed in the dialogue, is strongly implied and is a source of vulnerability in 1950s Britain, where same-sex relationships were illegal. Jo\'s occasional cruel references to his sexuality reveal the casual homophobia of the period, even among those who are themselves marginalised. Geof\'s relationship with Jo challenges conventional gender roles: he performs the domestic and nurturing functions traditionally assigned to women, while Jo is emotionally guarded and sometimes aggressive. Helen\'s hostility towards Geof — culminating in his departure — represents society\'s rejection of non-conforming relationships and gender performances. Geof\'s expulsion from the flat is one of the play\'s most painful moments, as it deprives Jo of the only person who has consistently put her needs first.',
