      'WJEC Eduqas Component 1 Section B assesses your response to A Taste of Honey through an extract-based question. You must analyse the given extract in detail before discussing the play as a whole. Spend approximately 15 minutes on the extract and 25 minutes on the wider play.',
      'Delaney\'s dialogue is naturalistic, so analyse it carefully: look for subtext (what characters mean versus what they say), humour as a defence mechanism, cliche as emotional avoidance, and silence or interruption as indicators of tension.',
      'Always refer to Delaney as the playwright who constructs meaning. Phrases such as "Delaney presents," "Delaney suggests," and "Delaney uses the character of X to explore" demonstrate awareness of authorial intent, which WJEC examiners specifically reward.',
      'Context should support your analysis, not replace it. A sentence linking Jo\'s situation to the limited options available to working-class women in 1950s Salford is more effective than a paragraph of historical background. Integrate context into every analytical paragraph.',
      'For the highest marks, explore the play as a piece of theatre. Consider staging, audience response, the use of music and direct address (features of Littlewood\'s production), and how different audiences — 1958 versus today — might respond differently to the play\'s treatment of race, sexuality, and class.',
      'Compare and contrast characters to develop your argument. The Helen-Jo comparison (mother-daughter parallels), the Geof-Peter contrast (different models of masculinity), and the Jimmie-Peter contrast (genuine versus transactional relationships) all offer rich analytical possibilities.',
      'Time management is critical. WJEC Eduqas allocates specific marks for each assessment objective: AO1 (response to text), AO2 (language, form, and structure), AO3 (context), and AO4 (SPaG). Ensure your response addresses all of these rather than focusing exclusively on one.',
      'Pay attention to stage directions and the physical staging of the play. Delaney specifies the flat\'s layout, the characters\' movements, and their physical interactions. Analysing how the staging creates meaning — for example, characters occupying or leaving the shared space — demonstrates awareness of the play as a theatrical text rather than a prose narrative.',
      'When discussing Helen, avoid the trap of simply condemning her as a bad mother. WJEC examiners reward nuanced analysis that recognises how social forces — poverty, lack of education, dependence on men — shape her choices. The most successful responses treat Helen as a complex, contradictory character rather than a moral lesson.',
      'Consider the significance of the play\'s title. "A Taste of Honey" refers to a brief experience of sweetness in an otherwise bitter existence — this applies to Jo\'s romance with Jimmie, Geof\'s time with Jo, and even Helen\'s hope that Peter will provide lasting happiness. Discussing the title as a structural metaphor can enhance your response.',
      'When analysing the extract, look for patterns in the dialogue: do characters listen to each other or talk past each other? Do they use questions, commands, or statements? Are their exchanges long or short? Delaney\'s naturalistic dialogue is carefully crafted to reveal character dynamics through conversational patterns, and identifying these patterns demonstrates sophisticated analytical skill.',
      'Do not neglect the play\'s ending. The final moments — with Helen discovering the baby will be mixed-race, Geof leaving, and Jo left singing a nursery rhyme — are deliberately inconclusive. Delaney refuses to provide a neat resolution, which is itself a statement about working-class experience: there are no easy endings when the social conditions that created the problems remain unchanged.'
